                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "<p>A client with gastritis asks the nurse at a screening clinic about analgesics that will not cause epigastric distress. The nurse would tell the client that which medication is acceptable to take?</p>",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "<p>Rationale:</p><p>Analgesics such as acetaminophen are unlikely to cause epigastric distress. Ibuprofen, indomethacin, and naproxen sodium are nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory medications (NSAIDs) and are irritating to the gastrointestinal tract, so they need to be avoided in clients with gastritis.</p>",
                        "id": "27eced6a6e7947c79817f22f8f13246b",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "30fd5a3344474f21aca991d0eb7aa836",
                                "content": "Portal vein"
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
