                        "content": "The nurse is caring for a client with acute bacterial gastroenteritis. Which of the following primary health care provider prescriptions would require a need for follow-up?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nGastroenteritis is a condition that causes acute vomiting and diarrhea and results in acute inflammation of the gastric and small bowel mucosa. It is usually bacterial or viral in nature. Clients are at risk for hypovolemia and electrolyte imbalances due to frequent vomiting or diarrhea, and treatment involves eradicating the causative organism and restoring fluid volume status. Option 1 is an appropriate nursing action, as the client’s intake and output provides valuable data regarding the client’s hydration status. Option 2 is an appropriate action, as antimicrobials are used to treat bacterial gastroenteritis. Option 4 is an appropriate action in the treatment of this condition to restore fluid volume status. Option 3 is the action that would require a need for follow-up with the primary health care provider, as antidiarrheals such as loperamide are not recommended in bacterial or viral gastroenteritis, as inhibiting diarrhea may slow the elimination of the pathogen from the body. Therefore, option 3 is correct, as it requires further follow-up.",
                        "id": "bc9607fa5fd74dfb856f923842881b2c",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
