                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nAcute gastritis refers to inflammation of the gastric mucosa after exposure to local irritants or pathological organisms. Key features of acute gastritis include rapid onset of epigastric discomfort, nausea and vomiting, hematemesis (or vomiting blood), gastric hemorrhage, dyspepsia (heartburn), and anorexia. Eliminate option 3 because a lack of appetite, or anorexia, not polyphagia (excessive hunger), is associated with acute gastritis. Next, eliminate option 5 because acute gastritis is associated with a rapid onset of symptoms, not an insidious, or slow, onset of symptoms. Therefore, options 1, 2 and 4 are correct.",
